hegemonic political perspective evolved organically, rather than as a product of a priori ideology.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aPolitical activistsxHistoryx20th centuryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aPolitical activistszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aPuerto RicansxPolitics and governmentx20th centuryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aPuerto RicansxSocial conditionsx20th centuryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aPuerto RicanszNew York (State)zNew YorkxPolitics and governmenty20th century. 0aPuerto RicanszNew York (State)zNew YorkxSocial conditionsy20th century. 0aRadicalsxHistoryx20th centuryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aRadicalszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial justicexHistoryx20th centuryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aSocial justicezNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aSocial movementsxHistoryx20th centuryxNew York (State)xNew York. 0aSocial movementszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 4aHistory : American History. 4aHistory : History. 4aHistory : Social and Cultural History. 4aNew York/Regional : New York/Regional. 4aSociology : Social Change. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Hispanic American Studies.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143846356840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781438463568423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781438463568/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles